Explanation:

A load balancer is added to distribute incoming traffic between multiple servers.
This improves availability and allows the website to handle more traffic.

Two servers are added so the website is not hosted on only one machine.
Each server contains Nginx, an application server, application files, and MySQL.

Nginx handles HTTP requests and can serve static content or forward requests to the application server.

The application server runs the backend logic of the website.

The application files are the website code base.

MySQL stores persistent data used by the application.

The load balancer uses the Round Robin algorithm.
Round Robin sends requests to each server one after another in order.
For example: request 1 goes to Server 1, request 2 goes to Server 2, request 3 goes back to Server 1.

This is an Active-Active setup because both servers are receiving traffic at the same time.

Active-Active means all servers are running and handling traffic.
Active-Passive means one server handles traffic while another server waits as backup.

The database uses a Primary-Replica setup.
The Primary database handles write operations such as INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE.
The Replica database copies data from the Primary and can be used for read operations.

The difference between the Primary and Replica nodes is that the application writes data to the Primary node, while the Replica node is mainly used for reading data and backup.

Issues:

There is still a SPOF because there is only one load balancer.
If HAProxy fails, users cannot reach the servers.

There can also be a SPOF if the Primary database fails and there is no automatic failover.

There are security issues because there is no firewall.
The servers and database may be exposed to unwanted traffic.

There is no HTTPS.
Traffic between the user and the website is not encrypted.

There is no monitoring.
If a server, service, or database fails, the team may not know immediately.
